9. When the cauſe is iuſt, and weighty, not light and frivolous; 

                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               , vel de lana caprina, as about the ſhadow of an Aſſe, or, the fleece of a Goat, as the Proverbs are: that is, for trifles, and things of no value: but as Suetonius ſaid to, and of Auguſtus, Quod nulli genti ſine juſtis & neceſſariis cauſis bellum intulit, that he never made war with any Nation without juſt and neceſſary cauſes.Sueton. in Aug Chap. 21. And
